<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Public Accounts Select Committee – written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PUB0005</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from London Borough of Lambeth</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lambeth is one of a growing number of councils that ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e becoming cooperative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> councils. That means putting people who use our services or live in our communities in control of the decisions that affect their lives. At its core it is about citizens, councillors and council staff working together to determine local outcomes and how best to deliver those. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has developed its own ambitious public service reform programme to become a cooperative council. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Empowering and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working with citizens (coproduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> central to our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> changing the way we think about the rol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e of local government in public service provision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of reducing public sector spending we are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> citizens to meet their needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In Lambeth we are seeking to build on the assets in our communities and to give power and control back to them, so that they can find ways of helping themselves and others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lead the lives they want to lead. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cllr Lib Peck</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Derrick Anderson</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Leader Lambeth Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Chief Executive  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lambeth Council </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">~</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What evidence is there that citizen-centred approaches to public service design, delivery and choice of provider can deliver better outcomes—ensuring not only better value for money, but also greater social, economic and environmental value?/ Why pursue citizen-centred approaches to public service design and delivery?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Our cooperative approach</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lambeth’s cooperative ambitions are built on a simple insight: that public services will achieve more when we do things </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people, rather than doing things </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people. Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> open, inclusive and democratically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accountable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have long recognised that decisions taken at the lowest possible level improves the quality of decisions and trust in public services.  But we also know that public services work better when we listen and act on the experience and insight of citizens; that we use resources more effectively when we help people to meet their own needs; and that we improve service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s by focusing on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that local people want to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our approach is part of a continuing journey. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2009 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our Cabinet and senior management were examining our future finances and felt we faced a bleak picture. We asked ourselv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es how local public services could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> deliver good outcomes for the coming budget reductions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the relationship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between the citizen and public services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> To answer those questions we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inclusive commission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> around 3,000 local people gave their views.  As a result we reached the following conclusions:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the likely pressures on finance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but sustained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">people will need to do more for themselves and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with others in their community.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he state </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will need to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and enable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Citizens need to be involved in the design and delivery of local services and activities – coproduction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Citizens can deliver services activities which make sense of local aspirations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we should be prepared to let go of power</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To make this work local government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs to support the community to do t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his, provide the infrastructure and build capacity. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Public services should be accessible,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local government provides accountability. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We see the benefits of citizen centred approaches in four main areas: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Utilising user and community expertise</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coproduction introduces better insight and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expertise to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the design and delivery of public services. No one understands services better than those that rely on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and communities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often have a strong sense of their own needs and the resources available to meet them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Aspire Wellbeing</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aspire Wellbeing was a day centre </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">run</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the council. Encouraged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by our cooperative direction of travel staff establish</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> themselves as a social enterprise - owned by the existing staff group and with the active involvement of service users and the local community.  The centre is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> thriving community resource maximising the local benefits it provides. This includes gym</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">membership, studio classes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affordable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meeting room hire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the income from which will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">invested in facilities for the community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aspire Wellbeing co–produce their services with all stakeholders; customers, volunteers, staff and the local communities.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">part of the government’s mutual pathfinder scheme they also help other social enterprise projects follow in their path; sharing their journey and helping others learn from their mistakes and successes.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improving and democratising</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Lambeth the cooperative council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provides citizens with the opportunity to drive the change and improvement they wish to see in their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It introduces a new level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of accountability where any citizen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, often working with councillors,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can influence the shape and design of local services without the need to wait for a consultation exercise or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scrutiny committee.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We believe that in the long term this will increase the capacity in our communities to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">design and deliver their local services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr style="height:157.1pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Cooperative Libraries</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Faced with the same challenges to library provision as the rest of the country we engaged with a wide range of people around each of our nine libraries. We provided detailed financial and service information and worked with the community develop wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at a successful library service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would look</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> like. A plan and budget has been set for each library </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that has been coproduced with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the community. This has resulted in Lambeth retaining all of its existing libraries whilst also reducing the necessary costs. Communities have taken on greater responsibility for libraries, and are tailoring the services offered by the libraries to meet the needs of that particular community.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A wider understanding of the resources available to us</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e believe that the real value of our cooperative approach lies in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bringing greater resources to bear on the challenges we face. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Local government revenues are a small, and diminishing, proportion of the total resources available in our borough. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is also a wealth of resources in our communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, among the people who live and work here, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who we can work with, enable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and support to achieve our shared outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In Lambeth we believe that providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reactive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people is neither sustainable nor effective.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We focus on the strengths of citizens to achieve good outcomes: c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oproduction and an asset-based approach enables the council to grow the existing assets and strengths within our communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enabling communities to meet their own needs.  </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The Workshop</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Workshop is an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on-going</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> project in West Norwood</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he first phase of the project involved setting up in a vacant shop in the town centre and holding over 540 conversations with residents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">generating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fresh ideas and seeking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways to overcome obstacles to collaboration.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second phase of the project is now underway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> establishing a number of ‘mini-lab’ projects which aim to establish a more collaborative, better-networked, self-sufficient community more capable of taking on further community-led cooperative activities. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o enable this transition from a ‘serviced community’ to a ‘collaborative community’ a whole system redesign is being tested </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exploring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> how:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 1) citizens interact with each other</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2) spaces and venues ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e used</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 3) networks operat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e and connect with each other</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">learning is acquired and shared</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 5) funding and inve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stment is secured and spent</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 6) procedures and processes are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">navigated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ownership of decisions </span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The scale of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cuts to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">revenue budget the council has faced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and continues to face</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is unprecedented.  Taking a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cooperative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> approach in such an environment enables the council to engage with its citizens, increasing their awareness of the scale of the challenge and gaining their input into how it is managed.  Undertaken conscientiously</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> enhances the basis for political decisions and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">results in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decisions that have greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ownership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within the affected communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The Young Lambeth Coop (YLC)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The YLC is a completely independent, community owned organisation that exemplifies the council’s ambition to transfer control and decision-making to local communities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">800 community hours have already been committed to the YLC’s development and 1100 adults and 650 young people expressed interest in being involved in its development.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">YLC members will be responsible for a £6m budget deciding what play and youth services are provided across the borough. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is programmed to deliver the council 24% cashable savings and be 23% cheaper than the current commissioning model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore it aims to commission an additional £3.8 million worth of services for young people over 5-years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of age</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, a significant proportion of which would not otherwise have been brought into the borough. </span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">To what extent is the government’s public service reform programme succeeding?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Like many other councils, Lambeth had experienced over 10 years of rising public sector spending,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> coupled with centrally determined targets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Towards the end of the last government, many were questioning whether we had reached the limits of this approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A focus on locally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">determined</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> outcomes, as we have done</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, allows </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focus on meeting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">populations’ aspirations, and to build more sustainable and holistic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approaches.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Strengthening the accountability of local government to its citizens has the potential to radically transform local areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but clearly any meaningful transformation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has to be based on a level of trust between central and local government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Localism </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a starting point towards a more locally determined approach. However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strong contradictions in government policy overall; while the Localism Act encourages decentralisation, NHS reforms and planning policy are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">paradoxically centralist.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> These tensions are exacerbated, or perhaps generated, by a departmental approach to public service reform across Whitehall that inhibits local government innovation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has not been the take up that might h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ave been expected of some of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">key elements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the Localism Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – such as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">powers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">communities to challenge and bid for public service d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elivery</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In Lambeth, these elements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> had very little impact.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment has failed to recognise a key point that Lambeth has learnt from its cooperative approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which is to invest in change and develop and build capacity in communities so they can deliver.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This coupled with the prevailing mantra of private sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and public sector bad dilutes its impact. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that a diverse local market will not only help us to deliver our outcomes more effectively, but also increase local employment and keep the value of public spending in the local economy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Public sector procurement has often been a barrier to this, but in Lambeth we are working to evolve our procurement policy and processes to pursue locally agreed definitions of value, and creating more opportunities for local businesses and social enterprises. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Here the Public Services (Social Value)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Act has been useful; although it contains few </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">formal powers, it has sent a signal to public services and the market about the importance of seeking value over cost, and encouraging social enterprises and other third sector providers to demonstrate the full worth of their activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (as demonstrated in the Aspire Wellbeing example)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the challenges of citizen centred approaches / and how can we ensure all citizen have influence?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Becoming facilitators and enablers</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> arguably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> three board approaches that councils can take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to meet the financial challenges we face</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 1) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cut your coat according to your cloth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and make cuts as funding reduces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">take a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more commercially orientated approach, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by balancing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the books through assets disposal, pricing, charging policy and efficiency strategies 3)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rovide the best outcomes for citizens at lower costs by putting the citizen at the centre of what we do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by enabling citizens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as Lambeth has done</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although we believe it to be the most effective option for reform, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> citizen centred approach to public services requires a significant change in the way councils work.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o embed citizen centred approaches public servants must change from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being ‘providers’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ‘facilitator</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ and ‘enabler</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lambeth we have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been building the infrastructure to make this happen.  We have introduced constitution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> changes to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> strengthen the role of councillors, as the voice of citizens, in the decision making process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and changed our key decision criteria to ensure the community priorities are at the heart of what we do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We have reorganised our structure and introduced a new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways of working for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e have introduced behaviour rather than competency-based job descriptions with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> five core behaviours </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">featuring in every job description</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: focuses on citizens, takes ownership, works collaboratively, integrity and committed to the borough.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Staff have undertaken specific training in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">collaborative techniques such as Appreciative Inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> closely with organisations that have experience in the field such as NEF, NESTA and Social Spaces. </span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Green Community Champions (GCC)</span></p><p style="margin:4pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">             </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">he Council made an open call to citizens to ask them if they would like to be green community champions and asked them to define what they wanted to do, supported by a single officer. There are now 500 champions working with over 60 groups and 5,000 residents on local environmental issues – from food growing to community energy projects. It has led to more innovation and community ownership than if the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ouncil had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">defined the network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">at the outset. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Equally, we recognise that this collaborative working is unfamiliar to many citizens. Our own research shows that there is an appetite among a significant proportion of the population to get involved, but current levels of par</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ticipation indicate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that traditional ways of engaging people are insufficient. If we want to increase participation significantly, then we must also ensure that the methods used appeal to the diverse communities in our borough. We therefore have begun a programme of innovation to find new ways of engaging people, for example using</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> online methods, hack days, pop-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up shops and appreciative inquiry.</span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Made in Lambeth</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ade </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ambeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a council facilitated hack-day type event </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> volunteers work together over single weekends to address particular challenges within the borough.  Volunteers come from a range of backgrounds including graphic designers, artists, project managers and community organisers.  Projects they have worked on include designing a brand new website and branding for the Young Lambeth Coop, accelerating the approach to digital inclusion across the borough, re-launching Vauxhall City Farm and marketing affordable pay-day loan products from the London Mutual Credit Union.  The council facilitates these events through coordinating project briefs and providing a location and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wifi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  However, the output is very much down to those who take part in the weekends.  This approach has enabled the council to harness the creativity of communities and helped create a more permissive council culture where creative changes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">designed by the community are put into practice.</span></p></td></tr></table><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Considerable work is also required to ensure that citizens are equipped with the skills to get involved.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Different levels of community infrastructure exist within different geographic communities or communities of interest.  Our work in West Norwood and around the Workshop (see</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> above)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has shown that capacity building among communities may be required to enable them to play a more active role. Involving citizens beyond the ‘familiar faces’ and ensuring all views are heard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a priority for a borough such as Lambeth that places a high value on equality. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, we are aware that sharp reductions in public funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">undermine essential resources that communities rely on and undermine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efforts to build capacity.</span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Community </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Freshview</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Freshview</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a community-led opportunity for residents to make a difference to their local area whether through brightening up a green space, giving a disused space a facelift or any other activity that improves the local environment.  The council provides nominal support such as plants and paint, expertise where needed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and support in accessing additional volunteers.  In addition to sprucing up an area Community </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Freshview</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has the benefit of bringing neighbours together and has been undertaken by more than 20 separate groups already.  This example has emphasised the value </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providing a clear and simple </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of council support for resident-led activity and highlighted how barriers to participati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on can be overcome through well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">publicised council support.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Evidencing what works</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and learning from early projects. </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With the huge range of services the council provides</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the sheer range of communities served</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the organisational culture has to become one which is more open to collaboration and innovation.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e expect this to be led from the top but have also implemented internal systems whereby good practice can be shared</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through action learning sets, blogs and toolkits,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and collaboration between staff and staff and citizens encouraged.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">innovation requires thorough evaluation and we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> gradually build</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an evidence base of what works. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From our early cooperative project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, called early adopters, we a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lso drew</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> learning about the management of risk, practical issues around governance, accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and holding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ic interest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and how to build capacity within the council and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> communities. </span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:478.8pt"><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Brixton Energy</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Brixton Energy is a not-for-profit co-operative based in Lambeth creating cooperatively owned renewable energy projects whose financial revenues stay within the local community. It is the first social-housing based renewable energy company in the country with a vision to create a greener future for Brixton.  In doing so it is generating energy, increasing Brixton’s energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resilience and security, raising awareness about energy efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tackling fuel poverty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and providing training and employment for local people.  It was established in cooperation with the council.  Since then five further roofs on the estate have been fitted with panels.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These are challenging times; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is less funding and an increased d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emand for some public services.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here are risks but there are opp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ortunities too. The Lambeth approach is transformational bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t we have achieved this through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a solid evidence base of support (through our Cooperative Council Commission)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> citizen engagement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and early prototyping to develop our thinking and draw learning around issues of risk, organisational structure, accountability, behaviour change and capacity building. We have found that in order for the approach to work, the council must help mitigate risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but more importantly by building new relationships and putting the citizen in control we are saving money. Ultimately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we believe that we will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">see a collaborative community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Lambeth</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where the council acts as a platform for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> collaboration, providing the right spaces and infrastructure to make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> happen. By empowering local people in this way we can give them back the power to change their lives and help those around them, fostering stronger more resilient communities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>